## Problem Statement

This study aims to develop a predictive model for forecasting total bicycle sales seven days in advance. The objective is to enable data-driven adjustments to inventory levels and pricing strategies, thereby optimizing operational efficiency and market responsiveness.

---

## Overall Observations

To address the challenge of forecasting total bicycle sales and informing inventory and pricing decisions, multiple predictive approaches were evaluated. After standardizing the dataset to ensure compatibility with regression and time series techniques, Multiple Linear Regression and Time Series Analysis were selected as the primary modeling frameworks.

### Regression Modeling
- Predictors selected: temperature, humidity, windspeed, and working day  
- Ridge Regression produced the lowest RMSE and most stable performance  
- Best suited for short-term (7-day) forecasting  

### Time Series Modeling
- Included season, year, month, holiday, weekday, working day, weather conditions, temperature, atemp, humidity, and windspeed  
- The 7-day moving average produced the lowest error across all time series methods  
- Effective for weekly operational planning  

### Key Insight
Both Ridge Regression and the 7-day moving average provide reliable short-term forecasts. Performance declines for long-term (30-day or more) predictions, so weekly forecasting is recommended.

